<TEXT>
a man who died of aids won a posthumous legal 
victory in his fight with a nail salon that refused to give him a 
pedicure 
the state court of appeals on wednesday upheld the 
constitutionality of a west hollywood ordinance that bans 
discrimination against people with acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome 
paul jasperson had sued jessicas nail salon for cancelling his 
july 1986 appointment for a pedicure after he mentioned to a client 
that he had aids 
im just overwhelmed with happiness i spoke at his funeral 
all of us wanted to win this for paul and for the millions of 
people with aids his attorney gloria allred said thursday 
in a march 1988 los angeles county superior court ruling a 
judge found that jasperson was denied service because of his 
illness but refused to issue an injunction 
judge lawrence waddington ruled that the pedicure potentially 
exposed salon workers to aids and the risk though marginal was 
unacceptable 
jasperson 37 died of aids in may but his appeal continued 
on wednesday the threemember second circuit court of appeals 
court ruled 21 to reverse the lower court ruling and enforce the 
ordinance 
the court said the ordinance by preventing discrimination 
serves a public health function by encouraging those with aids to 
make their illness known to providers of personal services who 
then can take precautions 
this case was extremely important because we were seeking to 
enforce the west hollywood city ordinance which had been used as a 
model and copied by many other cities throughout the nation ms 
allred said 
attorneys for santa monica and los angeles which have similar 
ordinances had filed briefs on behalf of jasperson as did the 
city of west hollywood and the american civil liberties union of 
southern california 
</TEXT>
