<TEXT>
here is a chronology of key events in the 
nations worst drunkendriving disaster 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
may 14 church bus from radcliff ky carrying 67 people 
collides with pickup traveling the wrong way on interstate 71 near 
carrollton ky fiery crash kills 27 people 24 of them children 
may 16 larry mahoney a chemical plant worker who drove the 
pickup is charged with 27 counts of capital murder authorities 
say mahoney had a bloodalcohol level nearly 2 times the legal 
limit 
may 19 thousands gather on high school football field in 
radcliff to mourn victims funerals begin 
may 20 mahoney pleads innocent to charges kentucky begins 
crackdown on drunken drivers and offers free safety inspection of 
private buses 
july 22 carroll county grand jury indicts mahoney on 27 counts 
of wanton murder 
aug 24 national transportation safety board holds hearing on 
bus crash in louisville 
oct 10 mahoney released from jail on 540000 property and 
cash bond 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 29 national transportation safety board releases 
findings saying kentucky needs tougher drunken driving laws and 
that states should set a date for school buses not meeting 1977 
federal standards 
may 14 first anniversary of bus crash marked by ceremonies 
held in memory of the victims monument in their honor unveiled at 
radcliff cemetery 
june 3 federal officials approve highway signs marking the 
crash site on i71 
nov 8 mahoneys trial begins with jury selection 
nov 20 testimony begins 
dec 14 mahoney takes the stand says hes sorry for the bus 
crash and deaths he is accused of causing 
dec 21 after deliberating for 11 hours jury convicts mahoney 
of 27 counts of seconddegree manslaughter one count of drunken 
driving 12 counts of assault and 41 counts of wanton endangerment 
jury begins deliberating what sentence to recommend 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0052 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nations worst drunkendriving 
disaster has prompted federal and state officials nationwide to 
work to make school buses safer 
kentucky in particular has approved new safety standards for 
future school buses and is poised to toughen its drunken driving 
laws after the fiery bus crash that killed 27 people including 24 
children 
the crash happened when a church bus collided with a pickup 
traveling the wrong way on interstate 71 near carrollton ky a 
jury on thursday convicted the pickups driver larry mahoney of 
27 counts of seconddegree manslaughter 
the former school bus owned by the first of assembly of god 
church in radcliff ky burst into flames upon impact defense 
lawyers contended that safety defects in the 1977 bus caused the 
loss of more lives 
investigators said the victims were trapped inside the bus with 
only one working exit and were overcome by smoke from a fire that 
spread among highly flammable seats 
the magnitude of the tragedy exacerbated by its young victims 
ages has drawn attention from all parts of the united states 
theres been a lot of changes as a result of the carrollton 
accident than anything else weve seen said don carnahan 
director of pupils transportation in washington state 
since the may 14 1988 crash officials at all levels of 
government have taken steps to add emergency exits install less 
flammable materials reconsider the location of the gas tank on 
buses and restrict the use of older buses 
across the country school officials government regulators and 
bus manufacturers say the crash has torpedoed a decade of 
confidence in the safety of school buses confidence dating back 
to the last extensive changes in federal regulations in 1977 
the crash has caused more dialogue within the industry than 
any other accident in recent history said ray kroll director of 
transportation for minneapolis schools and president of the 
national association for pupil transportation 
in kentucky the state school board approved new safety 
regulations in july for new school buses that will require them to 
have roofescape hatches fire resistant interiors and a wider 
space by the emergency exit 
those were among some of the recommendations made by the 
national transportation safety board after it concluded an 
investigation of the bus crash 
the board also urged the state to enact stricter laws for 
driving under the influence 
in its final report the board praised the work of a task force 
on drunken driving appointed by gov wallace wilkinson 
among the task force recommendations was proposed legislation 
that would make it an offense for any driver to test above a 010 
level on a blood alcohol level current law presumes that a driver 
is intoxicated if they have a test at that level 
a state attorney generals task force later recommended the 
state lower the bloodalcohol level at which a person would be 
considered legally drunk 
both proposals among numerous others will be dealt with when 
the state legislature convenes in january 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891222-0053 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
taking advantage of chaos in the 
