manuel antonio noriegas longstanding 
relationship with the cia could pose problems for federal 
prosecutors if the deposed panamanian strongman is caught and 
brought to trial on us drug trafficking charges government 
sources say 
federal prosecutors expect noriega would try to force the 
government to drop charges against him by seeking court disclosure 
of classified information that he was an informant for the spy 
agency these officials added 
such an approach would mirror the legal defense strategy used by 
oliver north and others with some success in the irancontra 
affair in which independent counsel lawrence e walsh was forced 
to drop some key charges when the government refused to allow 
disclosure of secrets in open court 
at the same time justice department officials said thursday 
they do not expect the secrecy problems in noriegas case to 
scuttle any of the charges that the panamanian helped colombian 
drug lords smuggle cocaine and marijuana through panama to this 
country 
noriega was indicted in 1988 by grand juries in miami and tampa 
fla 
prosecutors are anticipating that noriega will claim that his 
alleged drug activities were sanctioned by the us government 
because he was a cia informant 
but the government is prepared to offer evidence that none of 
the drugtrafficking activity was approved by the us government 
said one source speaking on condition of anonymity prosecutors 
will argue that just because noriega may have been an informant for 
the cia or the drug enforcement administration he is not immune 
from criminal prosecution the source said 
the secrecy issues involving noriegas case were among the items 
discussed at a meeting about the case dec 15 attended by 
prosecutors top officials of the justice departments criminal 
division and other law enforcement agents said spokesman david 
runkel 
officials decided at that meeting to try noriega first on 
charges filed in miami that he took a 46 million bribe from 
colombias medellin cartel to protect cocainesmuggling and 
moneylaundering operations in panama 
runkel said last weeks meeting had been scheduled for several 
weeks and was not convened in anticipation of the us invasion of 
panama 
the secrecy problems in noriegas case were termed 
manageable by one official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity but the official quickly conceded that irancontra 
prosecutors probably thought the same thing about their case 
against former white house aide north 
walsh was forced to drop major charges that north conspired to 
divert usiran arms sale proceeds to the nicaraguan rebels 
because the government wouldnt release information deemed relevant 
to the defense the classified information procedures act empowers 
judges to dismiss criminal charges if the government refuses to 
allow the disclosure of secrets needed for a trial 
north was convicted of charges that he tried to cover up his 
involvement in the irancontra affair but all irancontra charges 
against a former cia agent joseph fernandez were dismissed 
recently when the bush administration blocked disclosure of 
classified information 
