<DOCNO> AP891222-0249 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
local telephone companies will lose their 
guaranteed profit margins on interstate revenues in 1991 under a 
regulatory plan for better service at lower costs the chairman of 
the federal communications commission said 
new fcc chairman alfred sikes fulfilling the promises of his 
predecessor dennis patrick said thursday that beginning jan 1 
1991 many local phone companies will switch from the current 
rateofreturn pricing system to an incentivebased regulation 
known as price caps 
in the meantime these companies will continue under the 
rateofreturn formula that allows them to earn 12 percent above 
their investments the fcc decided in a 40 vote 
price caps will apply to the revenues local phone companies 
collect from connecting their callers with longdistance companies 
local phone companies with more than 100 million in annual 
revenues will fall under price caps which the fcc says is designed 
to lower phone rates 
when the fcc imposed price caps on the american telephone amp 
telegraph co this year after two decades of rateofreturn 
regulation it said consumers would reap 900 million in savings 
over the next four years as atampt raised or lowered rates within 
certain inflationbased price bands 
rate of return for the local companies which was due to expire 
dec 31 will continue into next year pending completion of a more 
comprehensive study of the process 
sikes said the price cap is the best available means of 
ensuring the united states the kind of efficient and effective 
telecommunications system that it needs 
local phone companies have been earning 12 percent since 1986 
which a consumer advocate said was too high under current market 
conditions 
the record clearly shows the rate of return should be 
reduced gene kimmelman of the consumer federation of america 
said following the commissions vote consumers ought to be 
seeing rates coming down because the companies earnings are 
excessive here was a chance to cut out the fat 
but the commission said the 12 percent rate was still just and 
reasonable 
patrick the former fcc chairman had said earlier this year he 
wanted price caps for the local phone companies but his aggressive 
deregulatory approach ruffled many feathers in congress 
richard firestone chief of the fccs common carrier bureau 
said thursday he had every expectation of being able to work 
successfully with congress 
sikes made clear he was unsatisfied with the amount of 
investment the local phone companies have been making in new 
facilities and equipment under the current rateofreturn process 
this past fall when i addressed the us telephone 
association convention in san francisco i questioned the level of 
industry investment in new plant and facilities sikes said 
since then many companies have assured me that their plans for 
1990 and beyond involve steppedup modernization programs 
sikes noting his previous experience as overseer of the 
missouri public service commission said the costplus approach to 
pricing used there illserved the consumer 
firestone said the fcc expected to adopt a price cap scheme by 
the fall of next year while also completing its rateofreturn 
study at about the same time 
local phone companies must file comments on the present 
rateofreturn scheme by feb 16 
</TEXT>
