<TEXT>
speculators in orange juice and heating oil futures are having 
an especially merry christmas because of a recordbusting cold 
front that prompted fears of a florida freeze and created spot 
shortages of fuel 
most other commodity markets were fairly quiet ahead of the long 
holiday weekend 
frozen concentrated orange juice for delivery in january settled 
at 137 a pound friday on the new york cotton exchange about a 9 
percent increase from 126 a pound a week earlier the contract 
traded as high as 14225 on friday but finished the day with a 
steep loss as traders took preweekend profits 
on the new york mercantile exchange heating oil for january 
delivery rose 16 percent to 8174 cents a gallon from 7042 cents 
the dramatic rise in both markets was almost entirely due to the 
relentless southerly advance of a cold air mass that meteorologists 
rated as one of the most intense of this decade 
the leading edge of the chill that hit north florida early 
friday was expected to bring nearrecord lows to the entire state 
including the citrusgrowing region in the middle of the florida 
peninsula 
about 85 percent of floridas 1 billionplus citrus crop is 
still on the trees the last major killing frost on christmas day 
1983 damaged at least 30 percent of the orange crop 
citrus specialists estimated less than 5 percent of the states 
700000 acres of trees were protected by costly heaters or wind 
blowers 
but the 1983 freeze and another in 1985 prompted citrus growers 
to shift production further south so while the projected lows of 
15 to 29 degrees in the citrus belt would be enough to damage 
fruit analysts said the damage would probably be less severe than 
six years ago 
the situation was quite different in 1983 said celeste 
georkakis an analyst with cargill investor services inc if the 
groves were where they were then wed have the same effect but 
they arent 
this years florida orange crop is projected at 133 million 
boxes vs 170 million in 1983 but brazil has since become a major 
producer of orange juice and is expected to harvest a record large 
crop this year 
therefore ms georkakis said any frostdamage shortfall in 
